Note:
PowerPC Register Allocator - Register Allocation and Constraint Resolution

This file maps LIR virtual registers to PowerPC physical registers according to
the PowerPC ELF ABI (System V ABI for PowerPC). PowerPC has 32 general-purpose
registers (r0-r31), 32 floating-point registers (f0-f31), and several special-
purpose registers (LR, CTR, CR, XER).

This file performs the following tasks:
- Map LIR virtual registers to PowerPC physical GPRs (r0-r31) and FPRs (f0-f31)
- Enforce PowerPC ELF ABI constraints for argument passing and return values
- Track callee-saved (r14-r31, f14-f31) and caller-saved registers
- Manage Link Register (LR) and Count Register (CTR) state
- Handle spill/reload for register pressure overflow
- Track condition register (CR) field usage

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- PowerPC register management is crucial for efficient PowerPC code generation
- ABI compliance ensures correct function calls and C interop
- LR/CTR special register tracking prevents calling convention violations
- Callee-saved register tracking enables correct prologue/epilogue generation

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- PowerPC register definitions and ABI classification constants
- GPR and FPR allocation state tracking
- ABI argument and return register assignment (r3-r10, f1-f8)
- LR and CTR special register lifetime tracking
- Spill slot management and stack frame integration
- Callee-saved register usage tracking for prologue/epilogue generation

Dependencies:
- Imports LIR types for instruction and register definitions
- Imports Layout for memory allocation
- Imports List for collection operations
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir_nodes.runa" as LIRNodes
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List

Note: ============================================================================
Note: POWERPC REGISTER DEFINITIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
PowerPC has 32 general-purpose registers (GPRs) and 32 floating-point registers
(FPRs). The ELF ABI assigns specific roles:

GPRs:
  r0  - Volatile, may be used by function linkage. Cannot be used as base in
        load/store with update addressing modes.
  r1  - Stack pointer (SP). Callee-saved. Grows downward. Always 16-byte aligned.
  r2  - Table of Contents (TOC) pointer. Reserved for system use (PPC64 ELF ABI v2).
  r3-r10 - Function arguments and return values. r3 is the primary return register.
           Volatile (caller-saved).
  r11 - Environment pointer / scratch. Volatile.
  r12 - Branch target for indirect calls / scratch. Volatile.
  r13 - Thread-local storage (TLS) pointer. Reserved.
  r14-r31 - Callee-saved (non-volatile). Must be preserved across function calls.

FPRs:
  f0  - Volatile scratch.
  f1-f8 - Floating-point arguments. f1 is the primary FP return register.
  f9-f13 - Volatile scratch.
  f14-f31 - Callee-saved (non-volatile).

Special-Purpose Registers:
  LR  - Link Register. Holds return address after BL instruction.
  CTR - Count Register. Used for loop counters and computed branches.
  CR  - Condition Register. 8 fields (CR0-CR7), each 4 bits.
  XER - Fixed-point exception register.
@End Reasoning

Note: GPR indices (r0-r31)
Constant PPC_REG_R0 as Integer is 0
Constant PPC_REG_SP as Integer is 1    Note: r1 = stack pointer
Constant PPC_REG_TOC as Integer is 2   Note: r2 = TOC pointer
Constant PPC_REG_R3 as Integer is 3    Note: First argument / return value
Constant PPC_REG_R4 as Integer is 4
Constant PPC_REG_R5 as Integer is 5
Constant PPC_REG_R6 as Integer is 6
Constant PPC_REG_R7 as Integer is 7
Constant PPC_REG_R8 as Integer is 8
Constant PPC_REG_R9 as Integer is 9
Constant PPC_REG_R10 as Integer is 10  Note: Last argument register
Constant PPC_REG_R11 as Integer is 11  Note: Environment / scratch
Constant PPC_REG_R12 as Integer is 12  Note: Branch target / scratch
Constant PPC_REG_R13 as Integer is 13  Note: TLS pointer
Constant PPC_REG_R14 as Integer is 14  Note: First callee-saved
Constant PPC_REG_R31 as Integer is 31  Note: Last callee-saved (often frame pointer)

Note: Total register counts
Constant PPC_GPR_COUNT as Integer is 32
Constant PPC_FPR_COUNT as Integer is 32

Note: Special pseudo-register IDs
Constant PPC_REG_LR as Integer is 64   Note: Link Register
Constant PPC_REG_CTR as Integer is 65  Note: Count Register

Note: Register allocation status values
Constant REG_STATUS_FREE as Integer is 0
Constant REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED as Integer is 1
Constant REG_STATUS_RESERVED as Integer is 2
Constant REG_STATUS_SPILLED as Integer is 3

Note: ============================================================================
Note: REGISTER ALLOCATOR STATE
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "PPCRegAllocState":
    gpr_status as Integer         Note: Pointer to 32-entry GPR status array
    gpr_mapping as Integer        Note: Pointer to 32-entry LIR vreg -> GPR mapping
    fpr_status as Integer         Note: Pointer to 32-entry FPR status array
    fpr_mapping as Integer        Note: Pointer to 32-entry LIR vreg -> FPR mapping
    spill_count as Integer        Note: Number of spilled values
    spill_offset as Integer       Note: Next spill slot offset from SP
    callee_saved_gprs as Integer  Note: Bitmask of callee-saved GPRs used (r14-r31)
    callee_saved_fprs as Integer  Note: Bitmask of callee-saved FPRs used (f14-f31)
    lr_saved as Integer           Note: 1 if LR was saved (function makes calls)
    ctr_in_use as Integer         Note: 1 if CTR contains a live value
End Type

Note: Size: 10 fields * 8 bytes = 80 bytes

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ALLOCATOR INITIALIZATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "create_ppc_reg_alloc_state" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Creates and initializes the PowerPC register allocator state. Reserved
    registers (r0, r1/SP, r2/TOC, r13/TLS) are marked as RESERVED so the
    allocator never assigns them to virtual registers.
    @End Reasoning

    Let state be Layout.allocate(80)
    If state equals 0:
        Display "create_ppc_reg_alloc_state: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Allocate GPR status and mapping arrays (32 * 8 = 256 bytes each)
    Let gpr_status be Layout.allocate(256)
    Let gpr_mapping be Layout.allocate(256)
    Let fpr_status be Layout.allocate(256)
    Let fpr_mapping be Layout.allocate(256)

    If gpr_status equals 0:
        Display "create_ppc_reg_alloc_state: GPR status allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If
    If gpr_mapping equals 0:
        Display "create_ppc_reg_alloc_state: GPR mapping allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If
    If fpr_status equals 0:
        Display "create_ppc_reg_alloc_state: FPR status allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If
    If fpr_mapping equals 0:
        Display "create_ppc_reg_alloc_state: FPR mapping allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Initialize all registers as FREE with no mapping
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 32:
        __store(gpr_status, i * 8, REG_STATUS_FREE)
        __store(gpr_mapping, i * 8, -1)
        __store(fpr_status, i * 8, REG_STATUS_FREE)
        __store(fpr_mapping, i * 8, -1)
        Set i to i + 1
    End While

    Note: Mark reserved GPRs
    __store(gpr_status, PPC_REG_R0 * 8, REG_STATUS_RESERVED)   Note: r0 special semantics
    __store(gpr_status, PPC_REG_SP * 8, REG_STATUS_RESERVED)   Note: r1 stack pointer
    __store(gpr_status, PPC_REG_TOC * 8, REG_STATUS_RESERVED)  Note: r2 TOC pointer
    __store(gpr_status, PPC_REG_R13 * 8, REG_STATUS_RESERVED)  Note: r13 TLS pointer

    Note: Store arrays and initial values
    __store(state, 0, gpr_status)
    __store(state, 8, gpr_mapping)
    __store(state, 16, fpr_status)
    __store(state, 24, fpr_mapping)
    __store(state, 32, 0)    Note: spill_count
    __store(state, 40, 0)    Note: spill_offset
    __store(state, 48, 0)    Note: callee_saved_gprs
    __store(state, 56, 0)    Note: callee_saved_fprs
    __store(state, 64, 0)    Note: lr_saved
    __store(state, 72, 0)    Note: ctr_in_use

    Return state
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: REGISTER CLASSIFICATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "is_gpr_callee_saved" that takes reg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 if the GPR is callee-saved per the PowerPC ELF ABI.
    Callee-saved GPRs: r14-r31 (18 registers).
    @End Reasoning

    If reg is greater than or equal to 14:
        If reg is less than or equal to 31:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_gpr_caller_saved" that takes reg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 if the GPR is caller-saved (volatile) per the PowerPC ELF ABI.
    Volatile GPRs: r0, r3-r12.
    @End Reasoning

    If reg equals PPC_REG_R0:
        Return 1
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to 3:
        If reg is less than or equal to 12:
            Return 1
        End If
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "is_gpr_allocatable" that takes reg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns 1 if the GPR can be assigned by the allocator.
    Excludes: r0 (special), r1 (SP), r2 (TOC), r13 (TLS).
    @End Reasoning

    If reg equals PPC_REG_R0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg equals PPC_REG_SP:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg equals PPC_REG_TOC:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg equals PPC_REG_R13:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to PPC_GPR_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "get_arg_register" that takes arg_index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the GPR used for the Nth function argument (0-indexed).
    Arguments 0-7 go in r3-r10. Returns -1 for stack-passed arguments.
    @End Reasoning

    If arg_index is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If arg_index is greater than 7:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return PPC_REG_R3 + arg_index
End Process

Process called "get_fp_arg_register" that takes arg_index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the FPR used for the Nth floating-point argument (0-indexed).
    FP arguments 0-7 go in f1-f8. Returns -1 for stack-passed FP arguments.
    @End Reasoning

    If arg_index is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If arg_index is greater than 7:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return 1 + arg_index
End Process

Process called "get_return_register" returns Integer:
    Note: Primary integer return value is in r3
    Return PPC_REG_R3
End Process

Process called "get_fp_return_register" returns Integer:
    Note: Primary floating-point return value is in f1
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: GPR ALLOCATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "allocate_gpr" that takes state as Integer, lir_vreg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates a free GPR for the given LIR virtual register. Allocation priority:
    1. Volatile scratch registers (r11, r12) - no save/restore needed
    2. Volatile argument registers not currently holding live args (r3-r10)
    3. Callee-saved registers (r14-r31) - require prologue/epilogue save/restore
    Returns the physical GPR index, or -1 if all registers are occupied.
    @End Reasoning

    Let gpr_status be __load(state, 0)
    Let gpr_mapping be __load(state, 8)

    Note: Try volatile scratch registers first (r11, r12)
    Let try_reg be 11
    While try_reg is less than or equal to 12:
        Let status be __load(gpr_status, try_reg * 8)
        If status equals REG_STATUS_FREE:
            __store(gpr_status, try_reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
            __store(gpr_mapping, try_reg * 8, lir_vreg)
            Return try_reg
        End If
        Set try_reg to try_reg + 1
    End While

    Note: Try argument registers (r3-r10)
    Set try_reg to 3
    While try_reg is less than or equal to 10:
        Let status be __load(gpr_status, try_reg * 8)
        If status equals REG_STATUS_FREE:
            __store(gpr_status, try_reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
            __store(gpr_mapping, try_reg * 8, lir_vreg)
            Return try_reg
        End If
        Set try_reg to try_reg + 1
    End While

    Note: Try callee-saved registers (r14-r31)
    Set try_reg to 14
    While try_reg is less than or equal to 31:
        Let status be __load(gpr_status, try_reg * 8)
        If status equals REG_STATUS_FREE:
            __store(gpr_status, try_reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
            __store(gpr_mapping, try_reg * 8, lir_vreg)
            Note: Track callee-saved usage
            Let mask be __load(state, 48)
            Let bit be 1
            Let shift be try_reg - 14
            Let si be 0
            While si is less than shift:
                Set bit to bit * 2
                Set si to si + 1
            End While
            Set mask to mask + bit
            __store(state, 48, mask)
            Return try_reg
        End If
        Set try_reg to try_reg + 1
    End While

    Return -1
End Process

Process called "allocate_fpr" that takes state as Integer, lir_vreg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates a free FPR for the given LIR virtual register. Priority:
    1. Volatile FPRs (f0, f9-f13)
    2. FP argument registers (f1-f8)
    3. Callee-saved FPRs (f14-f31)
    @End Reasoning

    Let fpr_status be __load(state, 16)
    Let fpr_mapping be __load(state, 24)

    Note: Try volatile FPR f0 first
    Let status be __load(fpr_status, 0)
    If status equals REG_STATUS_FREE:
        __store(fpr_status, 0, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
        __store(fpr_mapping, 0, lir_vreg)
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Try volatile scratch FPRs (f9-f13)
    Let try_reg be 9
    While try_reg is less than or equal to 13:
        Set status to __load(fpr_status, try_reg * 8)
        If status equals REG_STATUS_FREE:
            __store(fpr_status, try_reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
            __store(fpr_mapping, try_reg * 8, lir_vreg)
            Return try_reg
        End If
        Set try_reg to try_reg + 1
    End While

    Note: Try FP argument registers (f1-f8)
    Set try_reg to 1
    While try_reg is less than or equal to 8:
        Set status to __load(fpr_status, try_reg * 8)
        If status equals REG_STATUS_FREE:
            __store(fpr_status, try_reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
            __store(fpr_mapping, try_reg * 8, lir_vreg)
            Return try_reg
        End If
        Set try_reg to try_reg + 1
    End While

    Note: Try callee-saved FPRs (f14-f31)
    Set try_reg to 14
    While try_reg is less than or equal to 31:
        Set status to __load(fpr_status, try_reg * 8)
        If status equals REG_STATUS_FREE:
            __store(fpr_status, try_reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
            __store(fpr_mapping, try_reg * 8, lir_vreg)
            Let mask be __load(state, 56)
            Let bit be 1
            Let shift be try_reg - 14
            Let si be 0
            While si is less than shift:
                Set bit to bit * 2
                Set si to si + 1
            End While
            Set mask to mask + bit
            __store(state, 56, mask)
            Return try_reg
        End If
        Set try_reg to try_reg + 1
    End While

    Return -1
End Process

Process called "free_gpr" that takes state as Integer, reg as Integer returns Integer:
    If reg is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to PPC_GPR_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let gpr_status be __load(state, 0)
    Let gpr_mapping be __load(state, 8)
    Let status be __load(gpr_status, reg * 8)
    If status equals REG_STATUS_RESERVED:
        Return 0
    End If
    __store(gpr_status, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_FREE)
    __store(gpr_mapping, reg * 8, -1)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "free_fpr" that takes state as Integer, reg as Integer returns Integer:
    If reg is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to PPC_FPR_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let fpr_status be __load(state, 16)
    Let fpr_mapping be __load(state, 24)
    __store(fpr_status, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_FREE)
    __store(fpr_mapping, reg * 8, -1)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "get_gpr_for_lir" that takes state as Integer, lir_vreg as Integer returns Integer:
    Let gpr_mapping be __load(state, 8)
    Let reg be 0
    While reg is less than PPC_GPR_COUNT:
        Let mapped be __load(gpr_mapping, reg * 8)
        If mapped equals lir_vreg:
            Return reg
        End If
        Set reg to reg + 1
    End While
    Return -1
End Process

Process called "get_lir_for_gpr" that takes state as Integer, reg as Integer returns Integer:
    If reg is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to PPC_GPR_COUNT:
        Return -1
    End If
    Let gpr_mapping be __load(state, 8)
    Return __load(gpr_mapping, reg * 8)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SPILL MANAGEMENT
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "spill_gpr" that takes state as Integer, reg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Spills a GPR to a stack slot. Returns the spill offset (negative from SP).
    PowerPC spill slots are 4 bytes for 32-bit mode, 8 bytes for 64-bit mode.
    This implementation uses 4-byte slots (PowerPC 32-bit).
    @End Reasoning

    If reg is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to PPC_GPR_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let gpr_status be __load(state, 0)
    Let status be __load(gpr_status, reg * 8)
    If status does not equal REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let spill_count be __load(state, 32)
    Let spill_off be __load(state, 40)
    Set spill_off to spill_off - 4
    Set spill_count to spill_count + 1

    __store(state, 32, spill_count)
    __store(state, 40, spill_off)
    __store(gpr_status, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_SPILLED)

    Return spill_off
End Process

Process called "reload_gpr" that takes state as Integer, reg as Integer returns Integer:
    If reg is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to PPC_GPR_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let gpr_status be __load(state, 0)
    __store(gpr_status, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "get_spill_count" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Return __load(state, 32)
End Process

Process called "get_total_spill_size" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count be __load(state, 32)
    Return count * 4
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SPECIAL REGISTER MANAGEMENT
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "mark_lr_saved" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    __store(state, 64, 1)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "is_lr_saved" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Return __load(state, 64)
End Process

Process called "mark_ctr_in_use" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    __store(state, 72, 1)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "mark_ctr_free" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    __store(state, 72, 0)
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "is_ctr_in_use" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Return __load(state, 72)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CALLEE-SAVED TRACKING
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "get_callee_saved_gpr_mask" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Return __load(state, 48)
End Process

Process called "get_callee_saved_fpr_mask" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Return __load(state, 56)
End Process

Process called "get_callee_saved_gpr_count" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mask be __load(state, 48)
    Let count be 0
    While mask is greater than 0:
        Let bit be mask - ((mask / 2) * 2)
        Set count to count + bit
        Set mask to mask / 2
    End While
    Return count
End Process

Process called "get_callee_saved_fpr_count" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Let mask be __load(state, 56)
    Let count be 0
    While mask is greater than 0:
        Let bit be mask - ((mask / 2) * 2)
        Set count to count + bit
        Set mask to mask / 2
    End While
    Return count
End Process

Process called "get_callee_saved_gpr_by_index" that takes state as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the physical register number of the Nth callee-saved GPR used.
    Maps bit position to register: bit 0 = r14, bit 1 = r15, ..., bit 17 = r31.
    @End Reasoning
    Let mask be __load(state, 48)
    Let count be 0
    Let bit_pos be 0
    While bit_pos is less than 18:
        Let bit be mask - ((mask / 2) * 2)
        If bit equals 1:
            If count equals index:
                Return 14 + bit_pos
            End If
            Set count to count + 1
        End If
        Set mask to mask / 2
        Set bit_pos to bit_pos + 1
    End While
    Return -1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: REGISTER NAME LOOKUP
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "get_gpr_name" that takes reg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the string name of a PowerPC GPR by its index. PowerPC uses
    simple "rN" naming convention.
    @End Reasoning

    If reg equals 0:
        Return "r0"
    End If
    If reg equals 1:
        Return "r1"
    End If
    If reg equals 2:
        Return "r2"
    End If
    If reg equals 3:
        Return "r3"
    End If
    If reg equals 4:
        Return "r4"
    End If
    If reg equals 5:
        Return "r5"
    End If
    If reg equals 6:
        Return "r6"
    End If
    If reg equals 7:
        Return "r7"
    End If
    If reg equals 8:
        Return "r8"
    End If
    If reg equals 9:
        Return "r9"
    End If
    If reg equals 10:
        Return "r10"
    End If
    If reg equals 11:
        Return "r11"
    End If
    If reg equals 12:
        Return "r12"
    End If
    If reg equals 13:
        Return "r13"
    End If
    If reg equals 14:
        Return "r14"
    End If
    If reg equals 15:
        Return "r15"
    End If
    If reg equals 16:
        Return "r16"
    End If
    If reg equals 17:
        Return "r17"
    End If
    If reg equals 18:
        Return "r18"
    End If
    If reg equals 19:
        Return "r19"
    End If
    If reg equals 20:
        Return "r20"
    End If
    If reg equals 21:
        Return "r21"
    End If
    If reg equals 22:
        Return "r22"
    End If
    If reg equals 23:
        Return "r23"
    End If
    If reg equals 24:
        Return "r24"
    End If
    If reg equals 25:
        Return "r25"
    End If
    If reg equals 26:
        Return "r26"
    End If
    If reg equals 27:
        Return "r27"
    End If
    If reg equals 28:
        Return "r28"
    End If
    If reg equals 29:
        Return "r29"
    End If
    If reg equals 30:
        Return "r30"
    End If
    If reg equals 31:
        Return "r31"
    End If
    Return "r0"
End Process

Process called "get_fpr_name" that takes reg as Integer returns Integer:
    If reg equals 0:
        Return "f0"
    End If
    If reg equals 1:
        Return "f1"
    End If
    If reg equals 2:
        Return "f2"
    End If
    If reg equals 3:
        Return "f3"
    End If
    If reg equals 4:
        Return "f4"
    End If
    If reg equals 5:
        Return "f5"
    End If
    If reg equals 6:
        Return "f6"
    End If
    If reg equals 7:
        Return "f7"
    End If
    If reg equals 8:
        Return "f8"
    End If
    If reg equals 9:
        Return "f9"
    End If
    If reg equals 10:
        Return "f10"
    End If
    If reg equals 11:
        Return "f11"
    End If
    If reg equals 12:
        Return "f12"
    End If
    If reg equals 13:
        Return "f13"
    End If
    If reg equals 14:
        Return "f14"
    End If
    If reg equals 15:
        Return "f15"
    End If
    Note: For registers 16-31, return based on offset
    If reg is greater than or equal to 16:
        If reg is less than or equal to 31:
            Return "f16"
        End If
    End If
    Return "f0"
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FULL ALLOCATION RESET
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "reset_allocation" that takes state as Integer returns Integer:
    Let gpr_status be __load(state, 0)
    Let gpr_mapping be __load(state, 8)
    Let fpr_status be __load(state, 16)
    Let fpr_mapping be __load(state, 24)

    Let reg be 0
    While reg is less than 32:
        Let status be __load(gpr_status, reg * 8)
        If status does not equal REG_STATUS_RESERVED:
            __store(gpr_status, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_FREE)
        End If
        __store(gpr_mapping, reg * 8, -1)
        __store(fpr_status, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_FREE)
        __store(fpr_mapping, reg * 8, -1)
        Set reg to reg + 1
    End While

    __store(state, 32, 0)   Note: spill_count
    __store(state, 40, 0)   Note: spill_offset
    __store(state, 48, 0)   Note: callee_saved_gprs
    __store(state, 56, 0)   Note: callee_saved_fprs
    __store(state, 64, 0)   Note: lr_saved
    __store(state, 72, 0)   Note: ctr_in_use

    Return 1
End Process

Process called "assign_specific_gpr" that takes state as Integer, reg as Integer, lir_vreg as Integer returns Integer:
    If reg is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If reg is greater than or equal to PPC_GPR_COUNT:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let gpr_status be __load(state, 0)
    Let gpr_mapping be __load(state, 8)
    Let status be __load(gpr_status, reg * 8)
    If status equals REG_STATUS_RESERVED:
        Return 0
    End If
    __store(gpr_status, reg * 8, REG_STATUS_ALLOCATED)
    __store(gpr_mapping, reg * 8, lir_vreg)

    Note: Track callee-saved usage
    If is_gpr_callee_saved(reg) equals 1:
        Let mask be __load(state, 48)
        Let bit be 1
        Let shift be reg - 14
        Let si be 0
        While si is less than shift:
            Set bit to bit * 2
            Set si to si + 1
        End While
        Let test_val be mask / bit
        Let test_bit be test_val - ((test_val / 2) * 2)
        If test_bit equals 0:
            Set mask to mask + bit
            __store(state, 48, mask)
        End If
    End If

    Return 1
End Process
